## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 55(d)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55) provides the AMT exemption ($88,100 single / $137,000 MFJ / $68,650 MFS for 2025 per [Rev. Proc. 2024-40](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-24-40.pdf) § 3.13). [§ 55(d)(3)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55) phases the exemption out at $0.25 per $1.00 of AMTI above $626,350 (single / MFS) or $1,252,700 (MFJ). [§ 55(b)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55) then taxes the post-exemption AMTI at 26% up to a $232,600 break (or $116,300 for MFS, halved by [§ 55(b)(1)(A)(ii)(II)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55)) and 28% above. [§ 55(b)(3)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55) preserves [§ 1(h)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1) preferential rates on long-term capital gain and qualified dividends inside AMT — the tentative minimum is the smaller of the flat 26/28 schedule and a § 1(h)-style decomposition of preferential AMTI.

